  "text": "management, since most workloads are linked to near-sensor data processing [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] . On the other hand, the on-chip area budget is much tighter in IoT end-nodes. This squeezes the size of the I-Caches, also because they are often implemented with low-density memories which can operate at low voltages (e.g., standard-cell-based caches [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] ). This area squeeze is further exacerbated by the fact that there are multiple processors fetching in parallel, so the instruction memory system must deliver plenty of bandwidth, requiring complex logic, such as L0-buffers [CITATION_5] and broadcast-interconnect [CITATION_6] , which further increase the area dedicated to the instruction memory. Therefore, in this context it is highly valuable in term of area and energy-efficiency to keep the I-Cache small, while at the same time exploit the latency-hiding opportunities offered by prefetching to reduce the impact of cache-misses [CITATION_7] . Another factor is that the speed gap with the background onchip L2-memory (dense static random-access memory or even embedded flash), where the entire code is stored, is not so huge, so the amount of prefetched information can be kept small (a direct consequence of Little's law [CITATION_8] , [CITATION_9] ). This also works in the direction of making instruction prefetching highly effective.",
